{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502374"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:43:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:43:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1853"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1853"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.19,0.47,0.17,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1853"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78350"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1853"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1853"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63712"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"460"},{"type":"tags","id":"3463"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9078"},{"type":"tags","id":"9528"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"10994"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1523"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78350"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with right upper quadrant pain. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His abdomen is soft with mild tenderness in the right upper quadrant. Murphy\u0027s sign is negative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations are shown (Image 1). Abdominal ultrasound of gall bladder and biliary tree is performed (Image 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Conservative management","Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography","Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography","Laparoscopic cholecystectomy","Percutaneous transhepatic cholangiography"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with biliary colic and evidence of choledocholithiasis (common bile duct stones) based on abnormal liver function tests and ultrasound findings (Image). It is estimated that somewhere between 10-20% of patients with symptomatic gallstones also have stones in the common bile duct. These latter may not produce any symptoms and may only be evident on the basis on abnormal liver function tests. The management approach needs to address both the gallstones and the common bile duct stone. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step as it allows both diagnostic confirmation and therapeutic intervention to clear the common bile duct stone. This should be performed before addressing the gallbladder stones to prevent complications of biliary obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography\u003C/strong\u003E would provide excellent imaging of the biliary tree but is purely diagnostic and would delay definitive treatment which is already indicated based on the ultrasound findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic cholecystectomy\u003C/strong\u003E alone would not address the common bile duct stone. While combined laparoscopic cholecystectomy with intraoperative common bile duct exploration is possible, most centres prefer to clear the duct via ERCP first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConservative management\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given the presence of a common bile duct stone and abnormal liver function tests, which require intervention to prevent complications such as cholangitis or pancreatitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous transhepatic cholangiography\u003C/strong\u003E is typically reserved for cases where ERCP has failed or is not possible, such as in patients with altered surgical anatomy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In patients with symptomatic gallstones and common bile duct stones, ERCP is the preferred first-line intervention to clear the duct before cholecystectomy.","Abnormal liver function tests in a patient with gallstones should raise suspicion for common bile duct stones.","10-20% of patients with symptomatic gallstones have concurrent common bile duct stones."],"references":["Buxbaum J, Abbas Fehmi S, Sultan S, Fishman D, Qumseya B, Cortessis V et al. ASGE guideline on the role of endoscopy in the evaluation and management of choledocholithiasis. Gastrointestinal Endoscopy. 2019;89(6):1075-1105.e15. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30979521/","Narula V, Fung E, Overby D, Richardson W, Stefanidis D. Clinical spotlight review for the management of choledocholithiasis. Surgical Endoscopy. 2020;34(4):1482-1491. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32095952/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63712"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1853"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18282"},{"type":"media","id":"18283"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18284"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18282"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/74c2d645-9afe-4552-866c-1cb547698ed6.jpg","thumbUr